# builders/base/{{ .AppName }}

Per-app builder folder for `{{ .AppName }}`. Generated by
`flywheel add-app`; you can hand-edit any file here afterwards.

## What it does

These are all flywheel builder infra — none live in `apps`, which holds only
your application workload (`apps/base/{{ .AppName }}/`). GitRepository,
build-config, and git-auto-sync live in `flywheel-system`; ImageRepository and
ImagePolicy live in `flux-system` (where Flux's image-automation runs).

* **GitRepository** `{{ .AppName }}` (in `flywheel-system`) — Flux watches the
  in-cluster bare repo at `{{ .GitServerURL }}/{{ .Worktree }}.git`, triggers a
  Kaniko Job (via image-builder-controller) on every observed commit.
* **build-config** ConfigMap (in `flywheel-system`) — declarative replacement
  for legacy `.docker-builder-config` files. Edit `builds.yaml` to add
  multi-image build entries.
* **git-auto-sync** Deployment (in `flywheel-system`) — bidirectional sync
  between the host-mounted worktree at `/workspaces/{{ .Worktree }}` and the
  bare repo on the in-cluster git-server. Patches
  `GitRepository.spec.ref.branch` whenever you switch branches in the
  worktree. It runs in `flywheel-system` (flywheel infra) so the apps
  namespace holds only your application workloads.
* **ImageRepository + ImagePolicy** — Flux Image Automation watches
  `{{ .RegistryURL }}/{{ .ClientName }}/{{ .Image }}` and picks the
  newest tag (Unix-ts-prefixed) for IUA to bump into your manifests.

Edit `apps/base/{{ .AppName }}/deployment.yaml` manually — Flywheel
doesn't scaffold app workload manifests in v0.1.

## Namespace

The workload targets `{{ .AppsNamespace }}` (the `namespaces.apps` value from
`flywheel.yaml`). Pass `flywheel add-app --namespace <ns>` to place an app in a
different namespace; add-app then maintains a managed `apps/base/namespaces.yaml`
that creates any non-default namespace (idempotent — apps sharing a namespace
produce a single `Namespace` object). The default namespace is created
cluster-side, so no `namespaces.yaml` entry is written for it.
